WEBVTT

00:22.720 --> 00:24.700
CHAPTER XXV.

00:25.340 --> 00:27.620
I STRIKE THE JOLLY ROGER.

00:29.040 --> 00:35.820
I had scarce gained a position on the bowsprit, when the flying jib flapped and filled upon

00:35.820 --> 00:38.680
the other tack, with a report like a gun.

00:39.360 --> 00:44.940
The schooner trembled to her keel under the reverse, but next moment, the other sails

00:44.940 --> 00:48.600
still drawing, the jib flapped back again and hung idle.

00:49.720 --> 00:55.560
This had nearly tossed me off into the sea, and now I lost no time, crawled back along

00:55.560 --> 00:58.960
the bowsprit, and tumbled head foremost on the deck.

01:00.060 --> 01:05.260
I was on the lee side of the forecastle, and the mainsail, which was still drawing,

01:05.880 --> 01:09.060
concealed from me a certain portion of the afterdeck.

01:09.280 --> 01:10.980
Not a soul was to be seen.

01:11.600 --> 01:18.040
The planks, which had not been swabbed since the mutiny, bore the print of many feet, and

01:18.040 --> 01:23.980
an empty bottle, broken by the neck, tumbled to and fro like a live thing in the scuppers.

01:25.860 --> 01:29.440
Suddenly the Hispaniola came right into the wind.

01:30.060 --> 01:37.440
The jibs behind me cracked aloud, the rudder slammed too, the whole ship gave a sickening

01:37.440 --> 01:44.460
heave and shudder, and at the same moment the main boom swung inboard, the sheet groaning

01:44.460 --> 01:47.960
the blocks, and showed me the lee afterdeck.

01:48.980 --> 01:55.420
There were the two watchmen, sure enough, red cap on his back, as stiff as a hand-spike,

01:55.660 --> 02:00.080
with his arms stretched out like those of a crucifix and his teeth showing through his

02:00.080 --> 02:13.940
open lips, Israel hands propped against the bulwarks, his chin on his chest, his hands

02:15.200 --> 02:22.400
For a while the ship kept bucking and sidling, like a vicious horse, the sails filling, now

02:22.400 --> 02:29.500
on one tack, now on another, and the boom swinging to and fro, till the mast roamed

02:29.500 --> 02:30.780
aloud under the strain.

02:32.140 --> 02:38.720
Now and again, too, there would come a cloud of light sprays over the bulwark, and a heavy

02:38.720 --> 02:41.280
of the ship's bows against the swell.

02:42.020 --> 02:48.020
So much heavier weather was made of it by this great-rigged ship than by my home-made

02:48.020 --> 02:51.480
lopsided coracle, now gone to the bottom of the sea.

02:53.140 --> 03:01.120
At every jump of the schooner red cap slipped to and fro, but what was ghastly to behold,

03:01.120 --> 03:10.520
Neither his attitude nor his fixed-teeth-disclosing grin was anyway disturbed by this rough usage.

03:11.820 --> 03:18.780
At every jump, too, hands appeared still more to sink into himself and settle down upon

03:18.780 --> 03:25.980
the deck, his feet sliding ever the farther out, and the whole body canting towards the

03:25.980 --> 03:32.260
so that his face became, little by little, hid from me, and at last I could see nothing

03:32.260 --> 03:36.420
beyond his ear and the frayed ringlet of one whisker.

03:37.300 --> 03:43.620
At the same time I observed, around both of them, splashes of dark blood upon the planks,

03:44.060 --> 03:48.020
and began to feel sure that they had killed each other in their drunken wrath.

03:49.440 --> 03:55.580
While I was thus looking and wondering in a calm moment, when the ship was still, Israel

03:55.580 --> 04:02.720
hands turned partly round, and with a low moan writhed himself back to the position

04:02.720 --> 04:04.280
in which I had seen him first.

04:05.180 --> 04:12.620
The moan, which told of pain and deadly weakness, and the way in which his jaw hung open, went

04:12.620 --> 04:13.700
right to my heart.

04:14.180 --> 04:20.160
But when I remembered the talk I had overheard from the apple-barrel, all pity left me.

04:21.480 --> 04:24.740
I walked aft until I reached the main mast.

04:26.060 --> 04:30.240
"'Come aboard, Mr. Hands,' I said ironically.

04:31.020 --> 04:36.660
He rolled his eyes round heavily, but he was too far gone to express surprise.

04:37.660 --> 04:43.460
All he could do was to utter one word, "'Brandy!'

04:43.960 --> 04:50.020
It occurred to me there was no time to lose, and dodging the boom as it once more lurched

04:50.020 --> 04:55.580
across the deck, I slipped aft and down the companion stairs into the cabin.

04:56.700 --> 05:00.620
It was such a scene of confusion as you can hardly fancy.

05:01.680 --> 05:06.340
All the lock-fast places had been broken open in the quest of the chart.

05:07.280 --> 05:14.600
The floor was thick with mud where ruffians had sat down to drink or consult after wading

05:14.600 --> 05:16.400
in the marshes round their camp.

05:17.120 --> 05:24.860
The bulkheads, all painted in clear white and beaded round with gilt, bore a pattern

05:24.860 --> 05:26.300
of dirty hands.

05:27.060 --> 05:32.060
Dozens of empty bottles clinked together in corners to the rolling of the ship.

05:33.000 --> 05:37.960
One of the doctor's medical books lay open on the table, half of the leaves gutted out,

05:38.000 --> 05:40.180
I suppose, for pipe-lights.

05:40.920 --> 05:48.300
In the midst of all this the lamp still cast a smoky glow, obscure and brown as umber.

05:50.080 --> 05:51.640
I went into the cellar.

05:52.060 --> 05:57.540
All the barrels were gone, and of the bottles a most surprising number had been drunk out

05:57.540 --> 05:58.660
and thrown away.

05:59.440 --> 06:04.660
Certainly since the mutiny began not a man of them could ever have been sober.

06:06.000 --> 06:11.600
Foraging about I found a bottle with some brandy left for hands, and for myself I routed

06:11.600 --> 06:17.120
out some biscuit, some pickled fruits, a great bunch of raisins, and a piece of cheese.

06:17.920 --> 06:23.480
With these I came on deck, put down my own stock behind the rudder-head, and well out

06:23.480 --> 06:28.820
of the cockswain's reach, went forward to the water-breaker, and had a good deep drink

06:28.820 --> 06:35.020
of water, and then, and not till then, gave hands the brandy.

06:36.840 --> 06:40.540
He must have drunk a gill before he took the bottle from his mouth.

06:41.700 --> 06:46.200
I, said he, by thunder but I wanted some of that.

06:47.360 --> 06:50.500
I had sat down already in my own corner and begun to eat.

06:51.980 --> 06:54.160
Much hurt, I asked him.

06:54.910 --> 06:58.740
He grunted, or rather I might say he barked.

06:59.580 --> 07:04.440
If that doctor was aboard, he said, I'd be right enough on a couple of turns.

07:05.160 --> 07:10.920
But I don't have no manner of luck, you see, and that's what's the matter with me.

07:11.300 --> 07:14.940
As for that swab, he's good and dead he is.

07:15.320 --> 07:17.380
He added indicating the man with the red cap.

07:18.340 --> 07:20.200
He warn't no semen anyhow.

07:21.260 --> 07:23.780
And where might you have come from?

07:25.100 --> 07:31.100
Well, said I, I've come aboard to take possession of this ship, Mr. Hands, and you'll please

07:31.100 --> 07:33.300
regard me as your captain until further notice.

07:34.480 --> 07:37.040
He looked at me sourly enough, but said nothing.

07:37.860 --> 07:41.960
Some of the colour had come back into his cheeks, though he still looked very sick,

07:42.400 --> 07:46.160
and still continued to slip out and settle down as the ship banged about.

07:47.640 --> 07:49.200
By the by, I continued.

07:49.700 --> 07:54.980
I can't have these colours, Mr. Hands, and by your leave I'll strike them, better none

07:54.980 --> 07:55.700
than these.

07:57.380 --> 08:03.480
And again dodging the boom, I ran to the colour lines, handed down the cursed black flag,

08:04.120 --> 08:05.220
and chucked it overboard.

08:06.840 --> 08:12.260
God save the king, said I, waving my cap, and there's an end to Captain Silver.

08:13.400 --> 08:17.340
He watched me keenly and slyly, his chin all the while on his breast.

08:18.400 --> 08:27.540
I reckon, he said at last, I reckon, Captain Hawkins, you'll kind of want to get ashore

08:27.540 --> 08:28.240
now.

08:29.000 --> 08:30.340
Suppose we talks.

08:32.160 --> 08:39.840
Why, yes, says I, with all my heart, Mr. Hands, say on, and I went back to my meal with a

08:39.840 --> 08:40.440
good appetite.

08:41.660 --> 08:45.680
This man, he began, nodding feebly at the corpse.

08:46.680 --> 08:50.700
O'Brien were his name, a rank, irelander.

08:51.640 --> 08:57.260
This man, and me, got the canvas on her, meaning for to sail her back.

08:58.200 --> 09:06.540
Well, he's dead now, he is, as dead as bilge, and who's to sail this ship, I don't see.

09:07.120 --> 09:08.680
Without I gives you a hint.

09:09.480 --> 09:12.020
You ain't that man, as far as I can tell.

09:12.780 --> 09:20.960
Now, look here, you gives me food and drink and an old scarf, or anchorure, to tie my

09:20.960 --> 09:27.020
wound up, you do, and I'll tell you how to sail her, and that's about square all round,

09:27.080 --> 09:27.800
I take it.

09:29.300 --> 09:34.400
I'll tell you one thing, says I, I'm not going back to Captain Kidd's anchorage.

09:34.920 --> 09:38.480
I mean to get into North Inlet and beat her quietly there.

09:39.340 --> 09:42.140
To be sure you did, he cried.

09:43.660 --> 09:48.680
Why, I ain't such an infernal lubber after all, I can see, can't I?

09:49.680 --> 09:56.320
I've tried my fling, I have, and I've lost, and it's you has the wind of me, North Inlet.

09:56.920 --> 09:59.180
Why, I haven't no choice, not I.

09:59.560 --> 10:04.060
I'd help you sail her up to Execution Dock by thunder, so I would.

10:05.660 --> 10:09.720
Well, as it seemed to me, there was some sense in this.

10:10.100 --> 10:11.880
We struck our bargain on the spot.

10:12.520 --> 10:17.760
In three minutes I had the Hispaniola sailing easily before the wind along the coast of

10:17.760 --> 10:23.700
Treasure Island, with good hopes of turning the northern point air noon and beating down

10:23.700 --> 10:29.780
again as far as North Inlet before high water, when we might beach her safely and wait till

10:29.780 --> 10:32.200
the subsiding tide permitted us to land.

10:33.600 --> 10:39.640
Then I lashed the tiller and went below to my own chest, where I got a soft silk handkerchief

10:39.640 --> 10:41.620
of my mother's.

10:41.740 --> 10:47.900
With this and with my aid hands bound up the great bleeding stab he had received in the

10:47.900 --> 10:54.300
thigh, and after he had eaten a little and had a swallow or two more of the brandy he

10:54.300 --> 11:00.560
began to pick up visibly, sat straighter up, spoke louder and clearer, and looked in every

11:00.560 --> 11:01.740
way another man.

11:03.660 --> 11:05.940
The breeze served us admirably.

11:06.120 --> 11:12.180
We skimmed before it like a bird, the coast of the island flashing by and the view changing

11:12.180 --> 11:12.820
every minute.

11:13.800 --> 11:20.120
Soon we were past the highlands and bowling beside low, sandy country, sparsely dotted

11:20.120 --> 11:21.760
with dwarf pines.

11:22.860 --> 11:28.280
And soon we were beyond that again and had turned the corner of the rocky hill that ends

11:28.280 --> 11:29.660
the island on the north.

11:31.420 --> 11:37.120
I was greatly elated with my new command and pleased with the bright sunshiny weather and

11:37.120 --> 11:38.880
these different prospects of the coast.

11:40.040 --> 11:46.340
I had now plenty of water and good things to eat, and my conscience, which had smitten

11:46.340 --> 11:51.480
me hard for my desertion, was quieted by the great conquest I had made.

11:51.480 --> 11:57.920
I should, I think, have had nothing left me to desire but for the eyes of the cockswain

11:57.920 --> 12:03.360
as they followed me derisively about the deck and the odd smile that appeared continually

12:03.360 --> 12:04.460
on his face.

12:05.300 --> 12:13.900
It was a smile that had in it something both of pain and weakness, a haggard old man's

12:13.900 --> 12:14.240
smile.

12:14.720 --> 12:23.900
But there was, besides that, a grain of derision, a shadow of treachery in his expression as

12:23.900 --> 12:30.000
he craftily watched and watched and watched me at my work.

12:34.720 --> 12:36.680
CHAPTER 26

12:37.560 --> 12:39.900
ISRAEL HANDS

12:39.900 --> 12:44.460
The wind, serving us to a desire, now hauled into the west.

12:44.700 --> 12:50.200
We could run so much the easier from the northeast corner of the island to the mouth of the north

12:50.200 --> 12:50.540
inlet.

12:51.700 --> 12:57.440
Only, as we had no power to anchor and dared not beecher till the tide had flowed a good

12:57.440 --> 13:00.140
deal farther, time hung on our hands.

13:01.040 --> 13:03.660
The cockswain told me how to lay the ship too.

13:04.400 --> 13:08.960
After a good many trials I succeeded, and we both sat in silence over another meal.

13:10.020 --> 13:14.700
"'Gap'n!' said he at length, with that same uncomfortable smile.

13:16.160 --> 13:18.680
"'Here's my old shipmate, O'Brien.

13:19.520 --> 13:21.780
Suppose you was to heave him overboard.

13:22.080 --> 13:29.040
I ain't particular as a rule, and I don't take no blame for settling his hash, but I

13:29.040 --> 13:32.160
don't reckon him ornamental now, do you?'

13:32.160 --> 13:37.760
"'I'm not strong enough, and I don't like the job, and there he lies for me,' said I.

13:39.240 --> 13:45.640
"'This here's an unlucky ship, this Hispaniola, Jim,' he went on blinking.

13:46.700 --> 13:53.920
"'There's a power of men been killed in this Hispaniola, a sight a poor seaman dead and

13:53.920 --> 13:56.240
gone since you and me took ship to Bristol.

13:57.140 --> 14:00.580
I never seen such dirty luck, not I.

14:01.420 --> 14:04.260
"'There was this here, O'Brien, now.

14:05.000 --> 14:06.560
He's dead, ain't he?

14:07.060 --> 14:14.040
Well, now, I'm no scholar, and your lattice can read and figure, and to put it straight,

14:14.900 --> 14:21.960
do you take it as dead man is dead for good, or do he come alive again?'

14:22.800 --> 14:25.800
"'You can kill the body, Mr. Hands, but not the spirit.

14:26.040 --> 14:28.540
You must know that already,' I replied.

14:28.540 --> 14:32.520
"'O'Brien there is in another world and may be watching us.'

14:32.520 --> 14:34.560
"'Ah,' says he.

14:34.840 --> 14:36.660
"'Well, that's unfortunate.

14:37.720 --> 14:41.420
Appears as if killing parties was a waste of time.

14:42.280 --> 14:43.620
"'How, some ever.

14:44.260 --> 14:47.760
Spirits don't reckon for much by what I've seen.

14:48.200 --> 14:50.380
I'll chance it with the spirits, Jim.

14:51.480 --> 14:58.500
"'And now you've spoke up free, and I'll take it kind if you'd step down into that there

14:58.500 --> 15:00.260
cabin and get me a—'

15:00.540 --> 15:03.300
"'Well, ah, shiver me timbers.

15:04.160 --> 15:06.080
I can't hit the naimont.

15:06.680 --> 15:10.060
Well, you get me a bottle of wine, Jim.

15:10.660 --> 15:15.300
This here brandy's too strong for my head.'

15:15.300 --> 15:22.560
Now the cockswain's hesitation seemed to be unnatural, and as for the notion of his preferring

15:22.560 --> 15:25.760
wine to brandy, I entirely disbelieved it.

15:26.340 --> 15:28.120
The whole story was a pretext.

15:28.720 --> 15:30.240
He wanted me to leave the deck.

15:30.820 --> 15:31.920
So much was plain.

15:32.660 --> 15:35.940
But with what purpose I could in no way imagine.

15:36.580 --> 15:38.140
His eyes never met mine.

15:38.600 --> 15:44.680
They kept wandering to and fro, up and down, now with a look to the sky, now with a flitting

15:44.680 --> 15:46.500
glance upon the dead O'Brien.

15:47.460 --> 15:53.100
All the time he kept smiling and putting his tongue out in the most guilty, embarrassed

15:53.100 --> 15:58.100
manner, so that a child could have told that he was bent on some deception.

15:59.180 --> 16:05.220
I was prompt with my answer, however, for I saw where my advantage lay, and that with

16:05.220 --> 16:10.160
a fellow so densely stupid I could easily conceal my suspicions to the end.

16:11.420 --> 16:13.520
"'Some wine,' I said.

16:13.800 --> 16:14.860
"'Far better.

16:15.060 --> 16:17.820
Will you have white or red?'

16:18.780 --> 16:24.920
"'Well, I reckon it's about the blessed same to me e-shipmate,' he replied.

16:25.440 --> 16:27.780
"'So it's strong, and plenty of it.

16:27.780 --> 16:30.220
What's the odds?'

16:30.220 --> 16:32.180
"'All right,' I answered.

16:32.920 --> 16:38.160
"'I'll bring you port, Mr. Hans, but I'll have to dig for it.'

16:38.160 --> 16:40.760
With that I scuttled down the companion.

16:41.540 --> 16:47.840
With all the noise I could, slipped off my shoes, ran quietly along the sparred gallery,

16:48.520 --> 16:53.060
mounted the forecastle ladder, and popped my head out of the fore companion.

16:53.800 --> 16:59.040
I knew he would not expect to see me there, yet I took every precaution possible, and

16:59.040 --> 17:02.340
certainly the worst of my suspicions proved too true.

17:03.100 --> 17:08.540
He had risen from his position to his hands and knees, and though his leg obviously hurt

17:08.540 --> 17:14.640
him pretty sharply when he moved, for I could hear him stifle a groan, yet it was at a good

17:14.640 --> 17:17.740
rattling rate that he trailed himself across the deck.

17:18.420 --> 17:24.420
In half a minute he had reached the port's scuppers and picked, out of a coil of rope,

17:24.760 --> 17:31.080
a long knife, or rather a short dirk, discoloured to the hilt with blood.

17:31.080 --> 17:37.680
He looked upon it for a moment, thrusting forth his under-jaw, tried the point upon

17:37.680 --> 17:43.480
his hand, and then, hastily concealing it in the bosom of his jacket, trundled back

17:43.480 --> 17:46.340
again into his old place against the bulwark.

17:47.700 --> 17:49.600
This was all that I required to know.

17:50.460 --> 17:51.740
Israel could move about.

17:52.580 --> 17:58.080
He was now armed, and if he had been at so much trouble to get rid of me, it was plain

17:58.080 --> 17:59.540
that I was meant to be the victim.

18:00.340 --> 18:05.520
What he would do afterwards, whether he would try to crawl right across the island from

18:05.520 --> 18:10.580
north inlet to the camp among the swamps, or whether he would fire long Tom, trusting

18:10.580 --> 18:15.100
that his own comrades might come first to help him, was of course more than I could

18:15.100 --> 18:15.560
say.

18:17.160 --> 18:19.880
Yet I felt sure that I could trust him in one point.

18:20.740 --> 18:25.800
Since, in that our interests jumped together, and that was in the disposition of the schooner,

18:25.800 --> 18:31.200
we both desired to have her stranded safe enough, in a sheltered place, and so that

18:31.200 --> 18:35.960
when the time came she could be got off again with as little labour and danger as might

18:35.960 --> 18:36.580
be.

18:37.720 --> 18:42.440
And until that was done I considered that my life would certainly be spared.

18:44.540 --> 18:49.740
While I was thus turning the business over in my mind, I had not been idle with my body.

18:49.740 --> 18:57.220
I had stolen back to the cabin, slipped once more into my shoes, and laid my hand at random

18:57.220 --> 19:03.240
on a bottle of wine, and now, with this for an excuse, I made my reappearance on the deck.

19:05.120 --> 19:11.520
Hands lay as I had left him, all fallen together in a bundle, and with his eyelids lowered

19:11.520 --> 19:13.960
as though he were too weak to bear the light.

19:13.960 --> 19:19.680
He looked up, however, at my coming, knocked the neck off the bottle like a man who had

19:19.680 --> 19:26.540
done the same thing often, and took a good swig, with his unfortunate toast of here's

19:26.540 --> 19:26.860
luck.

19:28.020 --> 19:33.620
Then he lay quiet for a little, and then, pulling out a stick of tobacco, begged me

19:33.620 --> 19:35.000
to cut him a quid.

19:35.820 --> 19:44.100
Cut me a chunk of that, says he, for I haven't no knife, and hardly strength enough, so be

19:44.100 --> 19:44.960
as I had.

19:46.040 --> 19:50.920
Ah, Jim, Jim, I reckon I've missed stays.

19:51.900 --> 20:00.000
Cut me a quid, as I'll likely be the last lad, for I'm for my long home, and no mistake."

20:01.800 --> 20:09.280
Well, said I, I'll cut you some tobacco, but if I was you and thought myself so badly,

20:09.820 --> 20:12.740
I would go to my prayers like a Christian man.

20:14.300 --> 20:17.980
Why, said he, now you tell me why.

20:19.120 --> 20:23.600
Why, I cried, you are asking me just now about the dead.

20:24.340 --> 20:25.760
You've broken your trust.

20:26.300 --> 20:29.080
You've lived in sin and lies and blood.

20:29.080 --> 20:35.080
There's a man you killed lying at your feet this moment, and you ask me why?

20:36.040 --> 20:39.760
For God's mercy, Mr. Hands, that's why.

20:41.060 --> 20:47.080
I spoke with a little heat, thinking of the bloody dirk he had hidden in his pocket and

20:47.080 --> 20:50.420
designed in his ill thoughts to end me with.

20:51.140 --> 20:57.140
He, for his part, took a great draught of the wine, and spoke with the most unusual

20:57.140 --> 20:57.800
solemnity.

20:59.580 --> 21:09.000
For thirty years, he said, I've sailed the seas, and seen good and bad, better and worse,

21:10.000 --> 21:16.440
fair weather and foul, provisions running out, knives going, and what not.

21:17.740 --> 21:23.960
Well, now I tell you, I never seen good come a goodness yet.

21:24.620 --> 21:27.480
Him as strikes first is my fancy.

21:28.480 --> 21:31.800
Dead men don't bite, that's my views.

21:32.760 --> 21:34.220
Amen, so be it.

21:34.740 --> 21:38.500
And now you look here, he added, suddenly changing his tone.

21:39.380 --> 21:41.840
We've had about enough of this foolery.

21:42.620 --> 21:44.540
The tide's made good enough by now.

21:45.400 --> 21:51.280
You just take my orders, Captain Hawkins, and we'll sail slap in and be done with it.

21:51.900 --> 21:56.920
All told, we had scarce two miles to run, but the navigation was delicate.

21:57.440 --> 22:03.380
The entrance to this northern anchorage was not only narrow and shoal, but lay east and

22:03.380 --> 22:07.680
west, so that the schooner must be nicely handled to be got in.

22:08.580 --> 22:14.080
I think I was a good prompt subaltern, and I am very sure that Hans was an excellent

22:14.080 --> 22:21.020
pilot, for we went about and about and dodged in, shaving the banks with a certainty and

22:21.020 --> 22:23.520
neatness that were a pleasure to behold.

22:25.280 --> 22:29.680
Scarcely had we passed the heads before the land closed around us.

22:30.080 --> 22:34.880
The shores of North Inlet were as thickly wooded as those of the southern anchorage,

22:35.140 --> 22:41.060
but the space was longer and narrower and more like, what in truth it was, the estuary

22:41.060 --> 22:41.840
of a river.

22:42.640 --> 22:48.840
Right before us, at the southern end, we saw the wreck of a ship and the last stages of

22:48.840 --> 22:49.600
dilapidation.

22:49.600 --> 22:56.300
It had been a great vessel of three masts, but had lain so long exposed to the injuries

22:56.300 --> 23:02.400
of the weather that it was hung about with great webs of dripping seaweed, and on the

23:02.400 --> 23:07.500
deck of it shore bushes had taken root and now flourished thick with flowers.

23:08.700 --> 23:12.980
It was a sad sight, but it showed us that the anchorage was calm.

23:13.860 --> 23:22.860
Now, said Hans, look there, there's a pet bit for to beach a ship in, fine flat sand,

23:23.180 --> 23:30.160
never a cat's paw, trees all around of it, and flowers a-blowin' like a guarding on that

23:30.160 --> 23:30.880
old ship.

23:32.120 --> 23:36.320
And once beached, I inquired, how shall we get her off again?

23:37.240 --> 23:39.180
Why, so, he replied.

23:40.140 --> 23:46.660
You take a line ashore, there on the other side, at low water, take a turn about one

23:46.660 --> 23:53.700
of them big pines, bring it back, take a turn around the cap-stand, and lie too for the

23:53.700 --> 23:54.100
tide.

23:54.760 --> 24:01.140
Come high water, all hands take a pull upon the line, and off she comes, as sweet as nature.

24:02.040 --> 24:04.560
And now, boy, you stand by.

24:04.560 --> 24:13.720
We're near the bit now, she's too much way on her, starboard a little, so steady, starboard,

24:14.260 --> 24:18.540
larboard a little, steady, steady.

24:19.520 --> 24:26.180
So he issued his commands, which I breathlessly obeyed, till all of a sudden he cried, Now,

24:26.180 --> 24:32.680
my hearty, luff! and I put the helm hard up, and the Hispaniola swung round rapidly and

24:32.680 --> 24:35.160
stem on for the low wooded shore.

24:36.060 --> 24:40.760
The excitement of these last maneuvers had somewhat interfered with the watch I had kept

24:40.760 --> 24:43.760
hitherto, sharply enough upon the coxswain.

24:44.380 --> 24:49.300
Even then I was still so much interested, waiting for the ship to touch, that I had

24:49.300 --> 24:54.780
quite forgot the peril that hung over my head, and stood craning over the starboard bulwarks,

24:55.400 --> 24:58.500
and watching the ripples spreading wide before the bows.

24:59.740 --> 25:05.460
I might have fallen without a struggle for my life, had not a sudden disquietude seized

25:05.460 --> 25:07.420
upon me and made me turn my head.

25:08.280 --> 25:13.840
Perhaps I had heard a creak, or seen his shadow moving with the tail of my eye.

25:14.400 --> 25:17.580
Perhaps it was an instinct, like a cat's.

25:17.920 --> 25:24.600
But sure enough, when I looked round, there was hands, already half way towards me, with

25:24.600 --> 25:26.080
the dirk in his right hand.

25:27.240 --> 25:33.180
We must both have cried out aloud when our eyes met, but while mine was the shrill cry

25:33.180 --> 25:38.080
of terror, his was a roar of fury like a charging bully's.

25:39.600 --> 25:45.580
At the same instant he threw himself forward, and I leapt sideways towards the bows.

25:46.620 --> 25:52.180
As I did so, I let go of the tiller, which sprang sharp to leeward, and I think this

25:52.180 --> 25:57.060
saved my life, for it struck hands across the chest and stopped him for a moment dead.

25:58.080 --> 26:03.860
Before he could recover I was safe out of the corner where he had me trapped, with all

26:03.860 --> 26:05.020
the deck to dodge about.

26:06.000 --> 26:11.500
Just forward of the main mast I stopped, drew a pistol from my pocket, took a cool aim,

26:12.000 --> 26:16.860
though he had already turned and was once more coming directly after me, and drew the

26:16.860 --> 26:17.160
trigger.

26:17.980 --> 26:22.580
The hammer fell, but there followed neither flash nor sound.

26:23.140 --> 26:25.560
The priming was useless with sea water.

26:26.020 --> 26:27.840
I cursed myself for my neglect.

26:28.680 --> 26:33.560
Why had not I long before reprimed and reloaded my only weapons?

26:34.640 --> 26:39.340
Then I should not have been as now, a mere fleeing sheep before this butcher.

26:40.600 --> 26:44.540
Wounded as he was, it was wonderful how fast he could move.

26:44.540 --> 26:52.020
His grizzled hair tumbling over his face, and his face itself as red as a red ensign

26:52.020 --> 26:54.060
with his haste and fury.

26:55.020 --> 27:00.760
I had no time to try my other pistol, nor indeed much inclination, for I was sure it

27:00.760 --> 27:01.600
would be useless.

27:02.580 --> 27:08.720
One thing I saw plainly, I must not simply retreat before him, or he would speedily hold

27:08.720 --> 27:10.160
me boxed into the bows.

27:10.160 --> 27:17.960
As a moment since he had so nearly boxed me in the stern, once so caught, and nine or

27:17.960 --> 27:23.580
ten inches of the blood-stained dirk would be my last experience on this side of eternity.

27:24.700 --> 27:32.740
I placed my palms against the main mast, which was of a goodish bigness, and waited, each

27:32.740 --> 27:34.520
nerve upon the stretch.

27:35.380 --> 27:42.020
Seeing that I meant to dodge, he also paused, and a moment or two passed in feints on his

27:42.020 --> 27:44.240
part, and corresponding movements upon mine.

27:44.940 --> 27:50.400
It was such a game as I had often played at home about the rocks of Blackhill Cove, but

27:50.400 --> 27:55.200
never before, you may be sure, with such a wildly beating heart as now.

27:56.120 --> 28:01.480
Still, as I say, it was a boy's game, and I thought I could hold my own at it against

28:01.480 --> 28:03.560
an elderly seaman with a wounded thigh.

28:04.300 --> 28:09.780
Indeed my courage had begun to rise so high that I allowed myself a few darting thoughts

28:09.780 --> 28:15.320
on what would be the end of the affair, and while I saw certainly that I could spin it

28:15.320 --> 28:20.100
out for long, I saw no hope of any ultimate escape.

28:21.300 --> 28:29.000
Well, while things stood thus, suddenly the Hispaniola struck, staggered, ground for an

28:29.000 --> 28:34.740
instant in the sand, and then, swift as a blow, canted over to the port side till the

28:34.740 --> 28:41.400
deck stood at an angle of forty-five degrees, and about a punchin' of water splashed into

28:41.400 --> 28:44.960
the scupper holes and lay in a pool between the deck and bulwark.

28:46.300 --> 28:51.440
We were both of us capsized in a second, and both of us rolled almost together into the

28:51.440 --> 28:51.960
scuppers.

28:52.640 --> 28:58.140
The dead red cap with his arms still spread out, tumbling stiffly after us.

28:59.120 --> 29:05.060
So near were we, indeed, that my head came against the cockswain's foot with a crack

29:05.060 --> 29:06.460
that made my teeth rattle.

29:07.360 --> 29:12.840
Low and all, I was the first to foot again, for hands had got involved with the dead body.

29:13.720 --> 29:17.460
The sudden canting of the ship had made the deck no place for running on.

29:17.460 --> 29:24.480
I had to find some new way of escape, and that upon the instant, for my foe was almost

29:24.480 --> 29:25.640
touching me.

29:26.040 --> 29:32.580
Quick as thought I sprang into the mizzen shrouds, rattled up hand over hand, and did

29:32.580 --> 29:35.900
not draw a breath till I was seated on the cross-trees.

29:36.740 --> 29:38.740
I had been saved by being prompt.

29:39.580 --> 29:45.420
The dirk had struck not half a foot below me as I pursued my upward flight, and there

29:45.420 --> 29:52.620
stood Israel hands, with his mouth open and his face upturned to mine, a perfect statue

29:52.620 --> 29:54.800
of surprise and disappointment.

29:55.800 --> 30:00.600
Now that I had a moment to myself I lost no time in changing the priming of my pistol,

30:01.020 --> 30:06.500
and then, having one ready for service, and to make assurance, doubly sure, I proceeded

30:06.500 --> 30:10.240
to draw the load of the other and recharge it afresh from the beginning.

30:11.260 --> 30:14.080
My new employment struck hands all of a heap.

30:14.080 --> 30:21.400
He began to see the dice going against him, and after an obvious hesitation he also hauled

30:21.400 --> 30:28.840
himself heavily into the shrouds, and with the dirk in his teeth began slowly and painfully

30:28.840 --> 30:29.440
to mount.

30:30.580 --> 30:37.220
It cost him no end of time and groans to haul his wounded leg behind him, and I had quietly

30:37.220 --> 30:41.080
finished my arrangements before he was much more than a third of the way up.

30:41.740 --> 30:45.920
Then, with a pistol in either hand, I addressed him.

30:46.660 --> 30:52.080
"'One more step, Mr. Hands,' said I, and I'll blow your brains out.

30:52.980 --> 30:57.120
"'Dead men don't bite, you know,' I added with a chuckle.

30:58.300 --> 30:59.840
He stopped instantly.

31:00.260 --> 31:05.580
I could see by the working of his face that he was trying to think, and the process was

31:05.580 --> 31:09.500
so slow and laborious that in my newfound security I laughed aloud.

31:10.300 --> 31:16.280
At last, with a swallow or two, he spoke, his face still wearing the same expression

31:16.280 --> 31:17.920
of extreme perplexity.

31:18.520 --> 31:24.300
In order to speak he had to take the dagger from his mouth, but in all else he remained

31:24.300 --> 31:25.160
unmoved.

31:26.180 --> 31:33.560
"'Jim,' says he, "'I reckon we're fouled, you and me, and will have to sign articles.

31:34.470 --> 31:37.280
I'd have had you but for that there lurch.

31:37.800 --> 31:45.360
But I don't have no luck, not I, and I reckon I'll have to strike, which comes hard, you

31:45.360 --> 31:51.140
see, for a master mariner to a ship's yunker like you, Jim.'

31:51.140 --> 31:58.260
I was drinking in his words and smiling away, as conceited as a cock upon a wall, when all

31:58.260 --> 32:01.600
in a breath back went his right hand over his shoulder.

32:02.300 --> 32:04.640
Something sang like an arrow through the air.

32:04.920 --> 32:11.140
I felt a blow and then a sharp pang, and there I was, pinned by the shoulder to the mast.

32:12.040 --> 32:17.740
In the horrid pain and surprise of the moment, I scarce can say it was by my own volition,

32:17.980 --> 32:20.660
and I am sure it was without a conscious aim.

32:21.440 --> 32:25.460
Both my pistols went off, and both escaped out of my hands.

32:25.460 --> 32:27.900
They did not fall alone.

32:28.320 --> 32:36.460
With a choked cry, the cockswain loosed his grip upon the shrouds and plunged headfirst

32:36.460 --> 32:37.580
into the water.

